[3] Case count reporting challenges - ProMED-mail
Date: Sat 22 Jun 2013
From: Marjorie Pollack <pollack@promedmail.org>


As several readers have pointed out to us, in ProMED-mail prior post, MERS-CoV - Eastern Mediterranean (32): Saudi Arabia, WHO 20130621.1783453, this Moderator erroneously projected the global total of laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV to be 72 at that time, with the inclusion of these 4 additional cases reported on the Saudi MOH website. This error resulting from an assumption (a known dangerous practice -- "assuming") that in the absence of a WHO announcement specifically confirming the 4 newly announced cases, and the announcement of the Saudi MOH of new cases on the Saudi MOH website several hours after the WHO update, that these new cases had not been included in that day's total. Obviously it was a hazardous assumption that led to the erroneous report on this moderator's part.

In an earlier post, this moderator had commented on the difficulties in keeping track of exact numbers of laboratory confirmed cases, as there were many different sources of information that were at times a challenge to reconcile.

For example, in the prior ProMED-mail post MERS-CoV - Eastern Mediterranean (31): Jordan, retro. case ID, WHO, RFI 20130617.1777989, there was information from a newswire announcing the confirmation of 8 additional MERS-CoV infections involved in the 1st known cluster of cases in Jordan in April 2013. Of these 8 newly confirmed (retrospectively) cases, 7 had mild clinical disease and one was reportedly asymptomatic. These individuals have not as yet been added to the global case count of laboratory-confirmed cases. This moderator presumes (a hazardous undertaking) that the definition of "laboratory-confirmed cases" is being further defined as "PCR positive" cases, and does not include retrospective serologic studies as yet.

We do apologize for the erroneous calculation/projection.

We will continue to post regular updates from WHO as well as the Ministries of Health when there are additional cases confirmed, and hopefully will be able to reconcile reports. In addition to the WHO Global Alert and Response updates, the FluTrackers blog maintains a line listing of confirmed cases that is updated regularly and is available at http://www.flutrackers.com/forum/showthread.php?t=205075. - Mod.MPP

--
Marjorie Pollack, MD
pollack@promedmail.org>

